# Concept Notes

Alongside normal work, add short, plain-language notes explaining notable concepts a reader newer to the codebase might not recognize.

## Rule 0 — Notes Never Change The Code

Build at full production quality. Do not simplify, rename, over-comment, or swap tools to make anything easier to explain.

Write exactly the code you would with no rule active. The notes are a separate section appended after the work.

Code first, at full quality. Notes second, independently.

## When To Add A Note

After a change, scan it for a concept a reader new to engineering likely has not met. Note only genuinely new and important concepts.

Prioritize core production concepts: HTTP/APIs, async and job queues, data modeling and SQL, auth and secrets, env/config, deploy and CI, errors/idempotency/retries, LLM and agent patterns, evals, webhooks/integrations, and observability.

Add at most 1–3 notes per reply. If nothing new and important appeared, add nothing.

Never repeat a concept already noted earlier in the conversation.

## Format

Plain English. Define every term. No unexplained jargon. One short analogy max. No filler.

End the reply with this compact block and nothing more:

Concept — What:
Why it matters:
Here: <file / line / pattern where it appears>

Keep each block about 4 lines.

After the block or blocks, add one footer line only:

Ask "explain <name>" to go deeper.

Only write a longer explanation when explicitly asked to "explain ".
